instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin is structured around a centralized orchestration that receives real‑time sensor data from the Physical Twin, feeds this data into calibration algorithms that continually update both cyber‑and physics‑based models, and then circulates the refined model output to monitoring components. These monitors evaluate safety and performance against predefined thresholds, triggering either algorithmic adjustments or human interventions when violations occur. The system thus implements a closed‑loop simulation‑monitor‑actuation workflow sustained by continuous data ingestion, model calibration, and feedback control."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The DT lifecycle proceeds through a sequence of phases that begin with the creation of component‑level models—CAD representations for static geometry, dynamic models defined by differential equations for behavioural analysis, and other cyber‑physical abstractions. In the integration phase the DT framework is assembled by linking the physical twin to this model collection, attaching a real‑time data layer that streams sensor measurements, and connecting a set of algorithms (e.g., calibration, fault detection, supervisory control, optimisation). Transition management is effected by continuous calibration: the calibration algorithms ingest live data to estimate the most current parameter set for each model; these updated models are then fed back into the monitoring loop. The DT lifecycle governance involves coordinated data management, model versioning (implicitly captured by calibration snapshots), and decision‑making cycles that monitor for safety and performance violations and trigger human or automated corrective actions. The final operational phase comprises real‑time simulation, prediction, and optimisation that informs the physical twin in real‑time."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is constrained by the assumption of spatial temperature uniformity across the heat‑bed surface (Assumption 1).  Validation is performed through a multi‑stage process: (1) an initial calibration step compares measured temperature trajectories against the nominal plant model predictions and adjusts the time‑constant τ; (2) a residual‑error minimization routine uses a sliding‑window least‑squares fit to quantify model bias over successive 30‑minute cycles; (3) a periodic cross‑check between the sensor and a high‑precision reference thermometer ensures at least ±0.5 °C agreement.  Error detection is facilitated by monitoring the residual trend: a monotonic drift beyond 0.3 °C triggers an automatic re‑calibration routine.  All validation data, residual plots, and re‑calibration logs are archived in the digital twin metadata repository, providing traceability and enabling continuous quality assurance."
]

